>QOTT: have you voice trained?
I'm in the middle of it right now. Just went through a phase where I felt completely lost in the woods and then suddenly had a couple of things click for me and made some big strides forward. I'm still quite new to it, but it feels nice to make some progress, even if its only baby steps.

>do you think it's a meme?
https://voca.ro/1mhNf3qBufcW

No. As I say in the clip, voice training is trying to teach you to control muscles you normally can't consciously control, and so all the different exercises are basically ways of trying to trick yourself into learning the right unconscious muscle memory. Different tricks will work for different people, and I'd highly recommend people try different exercises and different approaches from different (reputable) sources online before giving up.

For example, I found Big dog, little dog, whisper sirens, hissing cat and sliding from and oooooo vowel to an eeeeee vowel didn't really work for me in learning to raise my larynx, but a certain weird exercise I saw on YouTube using mouth shapes *did* work for learning to raise my larynx.

But once I could, that same mouth shape exercise made me sound weird and terrible, so I went back to trying the others and suddenly found Big dog, little dog began to help me start creating the right kind of vocal tract shape to amplify the upper mid range frequencies while dampening low and super high frequencies.

Obviously my voice is still very much a work in progress, but I feel like I'm finally starting to get somewhere, and it's all because I kept trying different approaches until I found what worked for me.

There are plenty of approaches to this problem. You can attempt to integrate an error function over a bunch of integrals over function spaces, you can try to minimize the norm of the difference between the approximation operator and the original, or you try to keep only the eigenvectors corresponding to the largest elements in the spectrum. For a bounded self adjoint compact operator like an integral operator of this kind, the spectrum is discrete and bounded. There are very simple ways to calculate the "largest" eigenvectors for operators of this kind. Why would I prefer to use a neural network model instead? I don't think it's simpler than my current method.

Goal of the thread: Make a shopping list of things that you need, consider if there is any self care things you might be missing!
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

>>29349831
Bare minimum T, E2
SHBG, LH, FSH, Prolactin are useful to have. I'd argue these are potentially necessary. LH & FSH to check for gonadal suppression, SHBG to guesstimate free Estradiol. Prolactin is good to check if you're on Cypro or high dose E. Most blood testing utilities will sell these as a part of a package alongside T/E2.
Liver Function, Kidney Function, Thyroid, Full Blood Count, useful for additional safety if you're taking medication secondary to Estradiol i.e. non-GnRH based anti androgens.
The rest is issue-dependent. Some will argue DHT should be tested but serum concentrations are never representative of peripheral tissue concentration.

>That IS interesting, I had no idea. I was following the conventional wisdom of 1.5mm every 2 weeks with a pen.
Yea, I mean it's only one study I suppose.
https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32897622/
There's still no consensus on best protocol, but for myself re: depth, I go based off this pape:

>Moreover, the depth of the hair root in a miniaturized hair is 0.646 ± 0.140 mm. In terminal hairs, the depth of the hair root is 3.8 to 4.6 mm in Caucasians and 4.0 to 5.0 mm in Asians.
I've only just switched to 0.6mm from 1.2mm. I tried 1.5mm too but I was scared of damaging anything. I hadn't noticed any real significant regrowth in those slick areas, so I changed it up. >I'm clueless about the effects of prolactin and how to manage it, do you have any pointers about it?
Tbf I do need to look into Prolactin more regarding hair loss as per >>29360816. Prolactin plays a part in the development of the mammary alveoli (milk glands) and subsequent lactation. Estradiol regulates the release of Prolactin, the more E, the more Prolactin. Other drugs can cause rises in Prolactin too, like dopamine antagonists (some antipsychotics).

For enanthate, 5mg/7days or 10mg/14 days is common. Shorter interval is preferred for smoother levels, but for convenience or if you're scared of needles the longer interval doesn't hurt. For valerate, you'd do 2mg/3 days or 5mg/7days, but I'd prefer enanthate if you can get it. Smoother curve and more convenience.

That's monotherapy. If he insists on prescribing you an AA you should ask for 50mg bica/day and either 2.2mg enanthate/week or 1.2mg valerate per three days. This should give you levels ~150pg/mL, a bit high for a cis woman but common for trans. Ask him to schedule you a female hormone test three months in, so you can be sure the monotherapy is eliminating your T or the AA+lower dose is giving you roughly 150pg/mL. You'll want to test for E1, E2, LH, and T.

posts.com:
>>29394350
You can just take a bigger initial dose of a slower variant to get the "initial spike". They're better because they stay in your blood longer, producing a more even hormone level and necessitating injecting less often. Valerate every third day produces about the same hormone range as enanthate every ninth day, the difference is enormous.

"Spiky" levels aren't really a problem per se, cis women have huge spikes over their menstrual cycle, but maintaining a stable level stops you from getting PMS or menopause symptoms, which are not fun. They can also help you maintain a libido. Low T plus low E makes you basically an asexual eunuch, it can be pretty disturbing if that's not your thing. You'd be surprised how many trannies are distressed at having erectile dysfunction, even though it seems to me that NOT having erectile dysfunction should be a bigger source of dysphoria. What do I know, maybe they identify as women with erections.
>>29394369
Eh, neither is better or worse. Some AAs are pretty shit, cypro is fine for a few years but beyond that you want to either switch to mono or get an orchie, because it has a high risk of giving you benign tumours otherwise, and spiro will make you run to the bathroom every three hours to pee, it's legitimately enough to give you sleep deprivation, which will worsen the depression most trannies already have. Bica is fine even over long periods. A reason to avoid AAs is because they do go through the liver, and if you're already putting strain on it with alcohol or other medicines (or drugs), it's going to cause trouble eventually. There's some evidence that AA+cis female levels of hormone produce better feminisation than just shooting up with pregnancy levels of hormone like under monotherapy, but I know of good results from either method.

If your doctor will agree to give you bica, I'd say go for 50mg bica/day plus 1.2mg valerate/3 days. If he won't sign off on bica, go for monotherapy (2mg valerate/3 days).

There is a similar effect that does affect boobs. Estradiol will grow milk ducts, while progesterone will "terminate" them. A cis woman therefore is in a constant cycle of growing ducts and then stopping them, until she gets pregnant and the astronomical E2 levels she gets during the pregnancy just grows them constantly in preparation for lactation.
Prog thus will "terminate" your milk ducts, and since you don't have a menstrual cycle, they're not reset the way they are in cis women. I don't think the effect is permanent, but it's common knowledge that starting prog too early can stunt your breast development, even though starting prog at the right time (tanner 3) can help you along to tanner 4.

It's understandable anon. It's hard and it's work as >>29393677 said as well. It's been long enough that I think you'll agree the feelings aren't going to go away. Expressing them in a way that isn't so shame based and gooning isn't healthy for you and doesn't bring you happiness. So some of it is going to be self exploration and moderation based on your own niche. First step is forgiving yourself. It sounds cheesy, positive affirmations is a small way to start. You might even feel like you're lying to yourself at first. That's normal as you're trained to react a certain way and you're pushing against that current until your words can take root.
They can be simple and general, or specific to the situation. Repeat to yourself when you're feeling your thoughts start to smile, and in a small way argue against the negative thoughts until you win and then later try to self examine the reasons you felt that way.
Repeating a phrase outloud or in your head at least three times will help. Or until you pull yourself out of a shame spiral when those are occurring, and before you go to bed at night. Maybe some suggestions.
>I'm allowed to feel happy
>It's okay to be a bottom
>Feeling good isn't shameful
That's some suggestions but it can be anything. Counteract the shame voices with positive expressions.

Same for the reverse when it comes to women who transition to men because they feel like men have more power. Probably a higher chance of regret, but if someone is self-aware about all of that and they want to do something and prefer the results, there's nothing wrong with that.
